            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Sorting Algorithms — Overview

            Sorting is the process of arranging elements  
            in a specific order (usually ascending or descending).

            Examples:
            - Numbers → 1, 2, 3, 4
            - Strings → "apple", "banana", "orange"

            Why sorting matters:
            - Enables efficient searching
            - Makes data easier to analyze
            - Improves readability
            - Required by many algorithms

            Sorting transforms:

            Unordered → Ordered

            mermaid
            graph LR;
              A[5] --> B[1] --> C[4] --> D[2];
              D --> E[1] --> F[2] --> G[4] --> H[5];
            /mermaid
            </script>

          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Time Complexity

            The efficiency of a sorting algorithm  
            is measured using **Big-O notation**.

            ####O(n)####  
            ####O(n log n)####  
            ####O(n^2)####  

            - **n** = number of elements
            - Describes how runtime grows with input size

            Common complexities:
            - Quadratic → O(n^2)
            - Linearithmic → O(n log n)
            - Linear → O(n)

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              A[Input Size n] --> B[Algorithm];
              B --> C[Time Complexity];
              C --> D[Performance];
            /mermaid
            </script>


          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Comparison vs Non-Comparison Sorting

            ## Comparison-Based

            Elements are compared directly:

            if a < b

            Examples:
            - Bubble Sort
            - Insertion Sort
            - Merge Sort
            - Quick Sort

            Lower bound for comparison sorting:

            ####Ω(n log n)####

            ## Non-Comparison

            Do not compare elements directly.

            Examples:
            - Counting Sort
            - Radix Sort
            - Bucket Sort

            mermaid
            graph LR;
              A[Sorting Algorithms] --> B[Comparison];
              A --> C[Non-Comparison];
            /mermaid
            </script>

          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Key Properties of Sorting Algorithms

            ## Stability

            A sorting algorithm is **stable** if equal elements  
            keep their original relative order.

            Example:

            (2, A), (2, B)

            Stable → (2, A), (2, B)  
            Unstable → (2, B), (2, A)

            ## In-Place

            Uses constant extra memory:

            ####O(1)#### space

            ## Adaptive

            Performs better if data is partially sorted.

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              A[Sorting Algorithm] --> B[Stable?];
              A --> C[In-Place?];
              A --> D[Adaptive?];
            /mermaid
            </script>

          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
